What people are saying
By Julie M
“Post Covid Kingsday”
Apr 2022
The streets of Amsterdam seemed to exhale, thronged with crowds of party goers - The young, the old, tourists, families, and students - the variety of life! The energy in the air was palatable, immaculate - two years of pandemic induce anxiety and unease seemingly melted away and was untraceable in the afternoon air. The chilly streets of the canal district were alive with thousands of people moving past each other dressed head-to-toe in their finest orange fashions, accessorized with orange cowboy hats, feathery boas, novelty sunglasses and the region's finest beer! Impromptu dance parties formed seemingly at random, boats unloaded friends and picked up stray party goers. The streets were filled and bars empty, minus the stray barkeep charging a fiver for the downstairs toilet - Student collectives were open house parties for the locals, the nostalgic, the rich, the poor and the curious. Middle aged men sat in lawn chairs outside their pricey canal homes selling loose heinekens from dirty coolers at no particular price to the passer by. The streets, canals and twisted alleyways of the old city were resurrected. Reborn from a slumber, once again offering all of the mystery and beauty of the city to those willing to seek it.

The area

Neighborhood: Centrum
Amsterdam’s buzzing hub, with its sprawling network of tram rails and a seemingly constant flow of tourists and commuters, yields convenient access to some of the best sightseeing, shopping, and street life in Europe. Closest at hand are the Royal Palace, the quaint shops of Haalremmerdijk, the pedestrianized zones Kalverstraat and Dam Square with popular neighborhoods such as the Red Light District, and the Canal Ring hardly more than a moment’s stroll away. With the well-connected Centraal Station as Centrum’s base, it's easy to travel farther afield via one of the city’s iconic trams.

King's Day was, um, different
Apr 2019 • Friends
King's Day is drinking, crowds, music, drinking, more crowds, more drinking, street-side flea markets, drinking, and more crowds.

I am glad I experienced a King's Day but probably wouldn't do it again. I heard that Vondel Park was very busy with people and I think that might have been more pleasant.

We literally had to inch our way through shoulder-to-shoulder people to get down some streets. If you don't like crowds, you might not appreciate King's Day.

The city gets big APPLAUSE for the amazingly fast clean-up. We were staying right in the middle of King's Day activities and I was shocked that every little piece of trash and a million beer cans were ALL cleaned up early the following morning.
Written May 8, 2019

Absolutely fantastic
Apr 2019 • Friends
Having fancied doing King's Day for a few years now, decided this year we would visit. We knew it would be good but not quite as good as it was! The place is a sea of orange. Wear orange, you will be the odd one out if you don't. The more orange the better. The street party is on a huge scale. Pretty much from the station to the outer canal ring. Jordaan and Westerstraat in particular, is the place to be. A once in a lifetime experience. Everybody is well tanked up but we didn't see any trouble at all, which would not be the case in an English city! Book yourself up for King's Day. You will not be disappointed.

Salim E
Dubai, United Arab Emirates231 contributions
Party that would burn down the city if held in any other country
Apr 2019 • Friends
Amazing day to be in Amsterdam, party starts at around 11AM or 12 noon, and goes on till 8PM. You have DJs playing music on the streets all over the central area of the city. Designated roads are closed for cars, canals are filled with boats having their own parties and music. With the free flow of alcohol and “other substances”, a party like this would burn down the city 3 hours into the party; however as people are generally well behaved and used to the event, I would say the party was even safe for families which had babies in strollers moving from party to the next. Everyone dresses in orange, and I highly recommend dressing up as it’s simply more fun this way. I already liked Amsterdam; this day made me love it.
Written April 30, 2019
